{
    "id": "impersonal-verbs-grammar",
    "title": "Unit 27 Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass: Impersonal Verbs & Expressions",
    "curriculum_id": "unit-27-grammar",
    "voices": {
        "en": "en-AU-WilliamMultilingualNeural",
        "gr": "el-GR-AthinaNeural",
        "gr_en": "en-US-AvaMultilingualNeural"
    },
    "script": [
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Welcome... to the Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass for Unit 27: Impersonal Verbs. These are the verbs of 'It'. In English, we say 'It rains' or 'It seems'. In Greek, these verbs are powerful because they set the mood for the whole sentence. I'm William, and I'm joined by Athina. Athina... why do these verbs only have one single form?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γεια σας!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "These are"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Απρόσωπα ρήματα..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Impersonal. They don't have a person (I, you, he) because the 'Subject' is the situation itself, or the action that follows. They are always in the third person singular."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Let's start with the king of all impersonal verbs."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πρέπει."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Must."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Exactly."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πρέπει να φύγουμε..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "it must that we leave. You don't say 'I must', 'You must' in the verb itself."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πρέπει"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "stays static, and"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Να φύγουμε"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "tells us who is doing the leaving."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "It’s very efficient."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πρέπει να..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "followed by the subjunctive. What about"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Χρειάζεται;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "It means 'It is needed'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Χρειάζεται περισσότερος χρόνος..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "more time is needed. It’s passive in form but impersonal in usage."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Now, let's look at the weather. In English, we use 'It'. In Greek, the verb just stands alone."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Yes!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Βρέχει... Χιονίζει... Φυσάει."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "It rains. It snows. It blows (it's windy). You don't need a subject. The action is the subject."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "What about"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Φαίνεται"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "and"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γίνεται;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "The first means 'It seems'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Φαίνεται ότι θα βρέξει..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "it seems that it will rain."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γίνεται"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "means 'It is possible' or 'It can happen'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Δεν γίνεται!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "it’s impossible!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Pro Tip: Impersonal verbs often act as 'anchors' for the rest of the sentence. Athina, are there any that use the Genitive pronoun?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Yes!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Μου αρέσει."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "It pleases to me. In English, we say 'I like it', but in Greek, it’s impersonal: 'It is pleasing to me'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Σου αρέσει ο καφές;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "is the coffee pleasing to you?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "It’s a different perspective on reality. This concludes Unit 27. Master these anchors, and you'll navigate Greek sentences with ease."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Μπράβο! Σιγά σιγά όλα γίνονται. Γεια σας!"
        }
    ]
}